<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT/DTA-466 Diesel Engine Service (1990) - VIBRATION DAMPER, CRANKSHAFT, MAIN BEARINGS, FLYWHEEL AND
        CRANKCASE - REAR OIL SEAL &#38; WEAR SLEEVE - REMOVAL
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="5">
        <title>REMOVAL</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title></title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove two bolts from the flywheel and install two guide studs. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150709">7.9</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Engines equipped to accommodate automatic transmissions, will have a flex plate and a
                            reinforcing plate.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the remaining flywheel bolts and slide the flywheel out of the housing and off
                    the guide studs to remove it from the crankshaft. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150710">7.10</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . With the flywheel removed, the guide studs can be removed from the crankshaft flange.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Two methods are available to remove the rear oil seal. Method One uses rear seal remover
                            tool SE-4272. Method Two uses sheet metal screws and a pry bar.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Rear Oil Seal Removal (Method One)</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Assemble the puller plate with forcing screw from
                    <emph type="bold">SE-4272</emph>
                    onto the crankshaft flange using the two guide studs from the tool. With the plate attached, use a
                    punch and hammer to make four holes in the rear oil seal. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150711">7.11</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150709" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12146" filename="../figcg1/CG12146.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.9. Install Guide Studs.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150710" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12147" filename="../figcg1/CG12147.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.10. Remove Flywheel.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150711" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14150" filename="../figcg1/CG14150.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.11. Punch Holes in Oil Seal.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert hex head sheet metal screws into each of the punch holes. Turn the center forcing
                    screw in the puller plate and the seal will be removed from the flywheel housing (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150712">7.12</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Discard oil seal.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Rear Oil Seal Removal (Method Two)</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Use Method Two if the rear seal remover tool SE-4272 is not available.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Punch two holes into the rear oil seal and insert two hex head sheet metal screws.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a small pry and pry alternately on the screws to remove the seal from the flywheel
                    housing. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150713">7.13</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Discard oil seal.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>It is not necessary to remove the fly- wheel housing if all that is required is to replace
                            the crankshaft rear oil seal or wear sleeve.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef4150712" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12149" filename="../figcg1/CG12149.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.12. Remove Rear Oil Seal (Method One).</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150713" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12150" filename="../figcg1/CG12150.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.13. Remove Rear Oil Seal (Method Two).</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Wear Sleeve Removal (In Chassis)</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the rear oil seal removed, the wear sleeve can be removed using a muffler chisel
                    and air hammer. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk document="e415_134.xml" xrefid="ef4150714">7.14</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>BE CAREFUL NOT TO NICK THE CRANKSHAFT FLANGE DURING THIS PROCEDURE. USE THIS METHOD ONLY
                            WHEN THE REPAIR IS TO BE DONE IN CHASSIS WITH THE FLYWHEEL HOUSING IN PLACE.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Discard wear sleeve.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Wear Sleeve Removal (Out of Chassis)</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the flywheel housing removed, use a hammer and tap the O.D. of the wear sleeve.
                    Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk document="e415_134.xml" xrefid="ef4150715">7.15</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>This causes the wear sleeve to expand and slide off easily.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Discard the wear sleeve.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
